Why main() Method is Static?
public static void main(String[] args)

ğŸ‘‰ Reason:

JVM calls main() method without creating object.

Since no object is created at the start of program,
main() must be static so JVM can call it directly using class name.

ğŸ”¥ How JVM Calls main()

Internally JVM does something like:

Main.main(args);


Not like:

new Main().main(args); âŒ


Because no object exists yet.

ğŸ”¹ What If main() is Not Static?

Example:

public class Main {
    public void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}


Now try to run program âŒ

Compile Time Error:
Error: Main method is not static in class Main


Program will NOT run.

ğŸ”¥ Why JVM Needs static?

Because:

Program execution starts from main()

No object exists before program starts

So JVM cannot create object automatically

Therefore main() must belong to class â†’ static

ğŸ”¹ Simple Real-Life Example

Think:

Class = Blueprint of house
Object = Real house

Before building house (object),
You need entry point (main).

So entry point must exist without object.

ğŸ¯ One-Line Interview Answer

â€œMain method is static because JVM calls it without creating object of the class.â€

ğŸ”¥ Extra Knowledge

main() must be:

public â†’ JVM must access it

static â†’ No object required

void â†’ Does not return anything

String[] args â†’ For command-line arguments

